<P><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<IFRAME FRAMEBORDER=1 ALIGN=CENTER width=100% HEIGHT=200 SCROLLING=YES SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/Forum9/HTML/000900.html">
<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=0 WIDTH="95%"><TR ><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#F0DCA0" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Anthony Goeltz</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">possible spoilers, read with caution<P>Well, I finally finished the game today, so here is my "review", as promised. Basically, I'll just list the things I enjoyed, and of course the things I didn't enjoy. SO, here goes:<P>enjoyed-<P>I liked how if I just wore armor, and no leggings, then my charcter would be bare-assed. Same deal with leggings and no armor, bare-chested. The humor in this game was great. From the first 2 talking skeletons to Zandalor and his cards, this game got me rolling! I liked how the Dragon Armor was broken down into a few different quests, making it relatively easy to obtain, unlike the Diablo armor sets. The wishing well ruled! Moving stuff around was also very cool. I had that general store dude get on my case after I moved around a few of his boxes looking for the enterance to the bordello. The bordello! (My warrioress just happened to be homosexual...) It was cool how my resistances went above 100. I appreciated the fact that I was the hero, not me and my sidekick, not me and a band of cronies. ME. And just me. Probably the thing I liked best was how the game appeared to me like it was developed not really caring what certain groups might think about it. Like this: "OK people, we're gonna make this game with a bordello, swear words, and graphic language (I'm going to eat your living heart) no matter what some people may think". That's cool, props to Larian for not giving a damn!!! I liked how I could always see my character, even behind walls and stuff. Ok, that was a stretch, on to what I didn't like.<P>not-so enjoyable-<P>The skills. I wish the skills would not be available to those outside the profession. I'm a warrior with 10 intelligence, yet I can summon a deathknight and call downs meteors from the sky. I'm a mage with 10 strength, yet can kill a man in one hit with deathstrike, or hit something so hard it's stunned. I found that the pathfinding was rough. Pathfinding to me means being able to find your own way; not getting stuck running into a bush and not being able to move around it. Weapon balance, a big one. The weapon with the highest damage was a sword. Not an axe, not a maul, not a hammer or bardiche, but a sword. That's not right. Along the same line, I was annoyed that I couldn't break down a wooden door or smash open a wooden chest with my 150 weight axe. THE GAME MADE MY WARRIORESS TOO NICE!!! The 5 Black Ring members ALWAYS got the final word in before they died. Come on now, these people were evil. As soon as they opened their mouth to say something, my character should've slit their throats! Or at least give the option. THAT, made me mad, same with that stupid baby. That damn thing would've been cleaved in two! I guess they need to leave something open for a part II. How a skill (lockpicking) was made essential to be able to solve at least one quest (Treasure Map). No skill should be essential like that. Basically, if you were role-playing "right", only survivors (or a really sneaky warrior or mage) would have been able to complete that. That would be fine if there were other class-specific quests.<P><BR>Well, that's about it for now. It's bedtime and I'm braindead, so I may add more to this some other time. Overall, it was a decent game. On a 0-100% scale, I'd give it a 70%. That's better than 2/3 of the games out there, so not a bad rating at all. By all means, if you feel I'm too vague on something, ask me to explain it better and I'll try to give you a better answer.<P>------------------<BR>In thunderous song the steel I smite!</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Alrik Fassbauer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">In my personal POint of view, class-specific things are only wanted by those who are used to it.<P>For me, this is the first Class-Free Game I know, so I'll stick to it.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</IFRAME>
</FONT>
